1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:25,515
namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa namo tassa bhagavato

2
00:00:25,495 --> 00:00:30,461
Arahato samma sambuddhasa.

3
00:00:32,043 --> 00:00:35,709
Homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:41,658 --> 00:00:52,633
Just want to try and collect, this is an exercise of me trying to collect my thoughts around all the problems around rebirth.

5
00:00:54,942 --> 00:01:04,558
And what I've done is I've put it in sort of question form, which are the normal questions that sort of people ask.

6
00:01:05,118 --> 00:01:11,448
And then after each question, I'll just make sure that everybody's sort of got the idea.

7
00:01:11,850 --> 00:01:17,140
The first one, of course, that is interesting is what happens at death in Buddhist understanding.

8
00:01:18,582 --> 00:01:22,890
Actually the process, you know, what produces your next rebirth?

9
00:01:22,930 --> 00:01:25,715
I'm now presuming that there is such a thing, you see.

10
00:01:25,915 --> 00:01:29,742
What's going to affect your next rebirth?

11
00:01:32,066 --> 00:01:41,554
it's said that when you die, some image as to where you're going to go appears in the mind.

12
00:01:42,075 --> 00:01:47,189
And it's a product of your accent during your life.

13
00:01:48,301 --> 00:02:16,467
sometimes they say it can be a strong image an actual memory which takes you into your next life so if you for instance just as you died there came this image of you squashing a fly against the window this may take you into the deepest hells on the other hand catching a fly gently with the hands and

14
00:02:17,984 --> 00:02:21,971
Showing it the window may produce a very happy realm.

15
00:02:22,731 --> 00:02:29,342
So we'll come to this in a minute when we come to the different sorts of realms that you can end up in.

16
00:02:31,727 --> 00:02:40,262
But one thing that's interesting for us as Westerners is what has been studied about the process of terminal illness.

17
00:02:41,456 --> 00:02:48,490
There are five states that people go through, it seems.

18
00:02:49,673 --> 00:02:50,754
It's been well notated.

19
00:02:50,775 --> 00:02:55,704
The first book written on it was, I think, called Death and Dying by Elizabeth Kubler-Ross.

20
00:02:58,088 --> 00:02:59,251
Some of them you'll recognise.

21
00:02:59,311 --> 00:03:03,498
So when you're told, for instance, that you only have so long to live,

22
00:03:05,081 --> 00:03:08,728
The first thing, it's a bit of a shock, isn't it?

23
00:03:08,747 --> 00:03:11,633
So that's your first reaction, it's the shock, the horror of it.

24
00:03:13,094 --> 00:03:20,387
And the measure of that is the measure of ourself, the measure of our ego, you see, the measure of how much we're close to life.

25
00:03:21,808 --> 00:03:30,582
Once the shock is over, we tend to get a more happy, we tend to go into a sort of magic stage,

26
00:03:30,832 --> 00:03:33,795
a sort of, if I do the right thing, it'll pass away.

27
00:03:34,016 --> 00:03:35,057
They call it bargaining.

28
00:03:35,938 --> 00:03:41,525
So if I eat a thousand carrots, the cancer will definitely disappear.

29
00:03:42,306 --> 00:03:46,330
If I pray very, very hard, God will take this disease away from me.

30
00:03:48,473 --> 00:03:51,295
Then, of course, you visit the doctor and he says, no, it's getting worse.

31
00:03:52,417 --> 00:03:53,318
You are going to die.

32
00:03:54,218 --> 00:03:55,120
Of course, that's

33
00:03:55,741 --> 00:03:57,604
Then the next thing is, of course, you rage.

34
00:03:58,485 --> 00:04:00,229
You know, why me?

35
00:04:00,909 --> 00:04:11,549
I saw this lovely cartoon once, and there's a woman in bed, and there's a few friends around her, you see, and she's saying, why me?

36
00:04:12,009 --> 00:04:13,092
Why not one of you?

37
00:04:16,733 --> 00:04:18,355
Why are you saying that in your deathbed?

38
00:04:19,156 --> 00:04:19,576
Why me?

39
00:04:20,538 --> 00:04:21,579
Why not only you?

40
00:04:24,142 --> 00:04:30,831
And then after the anger passes, after the anger passes, there's this coming up with the reality of it.

41
00:04:31,151 --> 00:04:34,016
So you can't, there's no way around it now.

42
00:04:34,096 --> 00:04:35,798
So it's very depressing.

43
00:04:35,817 --> 00:04:37,019
Life's going to come to an end.

44
00:04:38,569 --> 00:04:43,725
And if the person gets through that, then they come to that state of equanimity, acceptance.

45
00:04:44,908 --> 00:04:45,831
Now just look at those.

46
00:04:46,954 --> 00:04:49,221
Shock, abject fear.

47
00:04:50,146 --> 00:04:51,987
Anxiety, yeah.

48
00:04:53,048 --> 00:05:02,740
A sort of weird mind state where you're trying to bargain your way out of the problem using magic, you know, running all over the world, taking this herb, that herb.

49
00:05:03,942 --> 00:05:09,168
Anger because it's just not working, nobody's helping you, there's no way out of the situation, frustration.

50
00:05:10,529 --> 00:05:12,913
Deep depression, deep sadness.

51
00:05:14,901 --> 00:05:15,983
Equanimity, peace.

52
00:05:17,946 --> 00:05:21,730
Fear, elation, what would you call that?

53
00:05:21,750 --> 00:05:26,255
Excitement, anger, depression, peace.

54
00:05:26,815 --> 00:05:35,846
Now, if there is a rebirth, you can see if you die in any of those states, that's the one that's going to carry you.

55
00:05:36,637 --> 00:06:01,564
And that's why in every religion they make this big effort when somebody's dying to get around them the images of their religion, which is going to make them peaceful, joyful, people giving them permission to go so the sadness disappears, singing hymns, all that sort of stuff, being with them in the last moments.

56
00:06:01,543 --> 00:06:10,697
just to give them that aura around them of equanimity, of peace, so that they themselves can die gently, can let go.

57
00:06:10,716 --> 00:06:26,639
So, I think all that the Buddhist literature would say is that the image which comes to mind as you leave the body will be determined by that state you're in, that's all.

58
00:06:27,180 --> 00:06:28,682
And it determines where you go.

59
00:06:30,653 --> 00:06:36,833
um if you want a um

60
00:06:38,095 --> 00:06:51,841
a full explanation of that, you can always look up the comprehensive manual of Abhidharma on page 124, and that will give you the details.

61
00:06:51,860 --> 00:06:57,172
So that's the process, it's called the death chutti, it's the death moment when you leave the body.

62
00:06:57,752 --> 00:07:01,098
It is going to be determined by the state of mind you're in,

63
00:07:01,636 --> 00:07:06,961
In Buddhist understanding, it may not particularly be that business around the illness.

64
00:07:06,980 --> 00:07:11,504
It could just be some big past regret that comes up.

65
00:07:11,725 --> 00:07:16,129
Things like that.

66
00:07:16,850 --> 00:07:19,812
The next question, of course, is what happens when you die?

67
00:07:20,613 --> 00:07:25,617
And here, unfortunately, the Buddhist tradition gives us an option.

68
00:07:26,738 --> 00:07:30,882
It depends what tradition you're in as to what's going to happen to you, it seems.

69
00:07:31,757 --> 00:07:48,838
the Theravada understanding, and so I'm told, you know, Zen and those Chinese forms of Buddhism simply say that you're reborn immediately into another space, another realm, another place.

70
00:07:49,088 --> 00:07:56,016
But the Tibetans have this idea of a bardo, where you stay for up to 49 days.

71
00:07:58,238 --> 00:08:12,916
And in that state, you seem to be bombarded, or you seem to come in contact with some forms of light, figures who emanate light, who all represent the six realms.

72
00:08:13,036 --> 00:08:14,798
And we'll come to that in a minute, somewhere.

73
00:08:14,978 --> 00:08:17,002
Yes, the next one.

74
00:08:17,021 --> 00:08:18,083
The six realms.

75
00:08:19,007 --> 00:08:24,576
The big one being the light of the enlightenment, of the dharmakaya, the body of the true law.

76
00:08:25,617 --> 00:08:32,648
And normally speaking, the person can't handle it, and they go for these softer lights for a different rebirth.

77
00:08:33,269 --> 00:08:36,153
And eventually they take rebirth wherever this soft light is.

78
00:08:36,614 --> 00:08:39,739
So the human realm, as I remember, it was yellow.

79
00:08:40,078 --> 00:08:40,860
I'm not absolutely sure.

80
00:08:41,942 --> 00:08:42,864
You have to look it up.

81
00:08:42,884 --> 00:08:43,083
Is it?

82
00:08:43,965 --> 00:08:45,807
I don't know, right?

83
00:08:45,788 --> 00:08:51,748
So then one goes towards that light and manifests as it were through that light.

84
00:08:58,967 --> 00:09:11,708
A more interesting explanation of libado, in terms of our life here and now, is they talk about the in-between point between one thought and the next.

85
00:09:12,190 --> 00:09:16,476
Just catching that moment is meant to be symbolic of libado.

86
00:09:19,241 --> 00:09:25,532
So it's that moment of that emptiness, when the mind stops, you might say.

87
00:09:27,841 --> 00:09:34,289
So that's what happens at death in these two major traditions.

88
00:09:36,667 --> 00:09:43,193
The next one is, of course, what are the realms of existence and how do they match what humans can experience?

89
00:09:43,214 --> 00:09:45,275
So, in other words, how they relate to us.

90
00:09:45,296 --> 00:09:54,787
Well, the six realms are hell, the animal realm, the hungry ghosts, the human realm, the angry gods, and the devas, the gods.

91
00:09:55,246 --> 00:10:06,318
And the hell realm, the worst of the hell realms, is reserved especially for those who've been cruel and horrible.

92
00:10:07,615 --> 00:10:15,706
But it really refers to, in terms of our experience, those states of mind that we ourselves would consider pretty hellish.

93
00:10:17,028 --> 00:10:21,595
You know, really delusive states, schizophrenia, deep profound depression.

94
00:10:22,355 --> 00:10:37,437
The big thing about a hell state, when we experience it, and all of us have experienced it in some way or other, is when we're in a bad state and just for a moment, or maybe even more than a moment, we don't think there's a way out.

95
00:10:38,918 --> 00:10:39,438
That's hell.

96
00:10:41,500 --> 00:10:48,807
I mean, if you're so depressed, if you're caught in a job and you just don't see a way out, you know what I mean?

97
00:10:49,508 --> 00:10:52,010
And that's really, I think, the quality of hell.

98
00:10:57,696 --> 00:11:03,701
The animal realm is the realm of the dull mind.

99
00:11:04,283 --> 00:11:06,764
So you get drunk or something like that, you know.

100
00:11:07,960 --> 00:11:16,653
And the problem with these two realms is that they're not very good places for enlightenment because they're too heavy.

101
00:11:17,195 --> 00:11:21,381
So the hell realm is obviously too painful, too deluded.

102
00:11:22,163 --> 00:11:24,726
And the animal realm, you don't have the intelligence.

103
00:11:25,006 --> 00:11:29,073
It's sort of not possible.

104
00:11:29,610 --> 00:11:39,168
The hungry ghost realm really refers to, you know, obsession, addiction, and these days we sort of know all about them.

105
00:11:40,993 --> 00:11:46,302
And that's really what it refers to, an addictive nature.

106
00:11:48,292 --> 00:12:04,099
So next time you serve yourself soup, especially when a huge desire to become it arises, you have to warn yourself, oops, if I die now, I'll be a hungry ghost.

107
00:12:04,539 --> 00:12:10,690
I won't be able to leave this pot forever.

108
00:12:11,051 --> 00:12:12,493
No, no, nothing's forever.

109
00:12:13,299 --> 00:12:23,793
The human realm is characterized by what we know as, you know, in Buddhist terms, remember, everything we say is always about the liberation, always about the enlightenment.

110
00:12:24,413 --> 00:12:30,000
It's characterized by joy and woe, joy and woe, you know, suffering and joy.

111
00:12:30,980 --> 00:12:32,462
And we have this intelligence.

112
00:12:32,802 --> 00:12:35,385
We can, you know, make our way out, make our way out of it.

113
00:12:35,986 --> 00:12:38,429
And that's the process, of course.

114
00:12:38,409 --> 00:12:50,278
the Vipassana is a technique we use, or in other traditions, Dzogchen, Zazen, is a technique we use to access that intelligence which is going to lead us out of this suffering.

115
00:12:50,298 --> 00:12:53,365
So that's specific to the human realm, you might say.

116
00:12:54,931 --> 00:12:58,496
The angry gods are always fighting, always at each other.

117
00:12:59,038 --> 00:13:02,985
So it's obviously a place where we're angry, frustrated, whatever.

118
00:13:04,046 --> 00:13:08,212
And finally the Devas is for the rich, the powerful and the famous.

119
00:13:08,232 --> 00:13:13,022
So you're just too happy, you just can't be bothered with practice.

120
00:13:13,042 --> 00:13:18,070
I mean, why bother, you know, when you're lying on the beach in Acapulco, you know.

121
00:13:19,720 --> 00:13:34,860
So they don't particularly relate directly to these five points of a terminal illness, but it shows you that there's some relationship between that.

122
00:13:36,038 --> 00:13:37,339
This isn't the fullness of it.

123
00:13:37,440 --> 00:14:00,865
If you look at a book called The Psychological Attitude of Early Buddhist Philosophy, a hell of a title, by Anagarika Govinda, there, of course, the later scholastics went and divided all these realms into myriad realms depending on the particular state you were in, especially the particular absorption you were in, the particular jhanic state.

124
00:14:00,845 --> 00:14:07,736
And all these different saints, these different paths, have a particular place to go to.

125
00:14:07,756 --> 00:14:15,331
So, I don't know whether these things exist or not.

126
00:14:15,912 --> 00:14:16,773
Who knows, you know?

127
00:14:17,794 --> 00:14:22,683
I've got this awful feeling that they're all here.

128
00:14:22,663 --> 00:14:24,908
They're all here around us.

129
00:14:25,370 --> 00:14:34,029
And just like the human realm is a jumble of hellish people, ghostly, these hungry ghosts, they're all around us here now.

130
00:14:34,070 --> 00:14:37,938
I can feel them, you might say.

131
00:14:43,690 --> 00:14:49,740
So there we have this whole thing about the way you die, the way you're reborn.

132
00:14:50,201 --> 00:14:56,533
Everything that we talk about the afterlife is actually a mirror in Buddhist understanding of what you can experience in the human life.

133
00:14:57,336 --> 00:15:03,807
So you can say it's just a creative imagination.

134
00:15:03,788 --> 00:15:07,032
You can take the position of believing it, we'll come to that in a minute.

135
00:15:08,013 --> 00:15:13,298
Or you can take it that in fact it is a holographic universe.

136
00:15:13,479 --> 00:15:15,280
Everything is virtually the same.

137
00:15:16,381 --> 00:15:17,984
Everything contains everything else.

138
00:15:18,924 --> 00:15:29,356
This would go back to the idea of the Indra's net, where each jewel at the joining of each of these little ropes of a net mirrors the whole universe.

139
00:15:29,336 --> 00:15:38,722
So why should any other realm be really outside what we can experience here in this realm?

140
00:15:42,027 --> 00:15:47,394
The next question is, what is the difference between rebirth and reincarnation?

141
00:15:47,716 --> 00:15:53,063
This whole thing is worked out in the Indian culture.

142
00:15:53,644 --> 00:15:57,910
You don't get much of this at all, as far as I know, in the Chinese culture.

143
00:15:58,010 --> 00:16:00,975
Of course, they believe in ancestors and stuff like that and rebirth.

144
00:16:01,395 --> 00:16:04,760
But in the old Confucian culture,

145
00:16:04,740 --> 00:16:13,856
the old ancient Chinese culture, there was obviously some idea of onward going like Christians have, but it was never sort of worked out in any great detail, I don't think.

146
00:16:15,119 --> 00:16:24,610
But the main difference between reincarnation and rebirth between the Hindu system, shall we say, and the Buddhist system is there's a nice image.

147
00:16:25,751 --> 00:16:28,355
The Hindu system would suggest a string of beads.

148
00:16:29,256 --> 00:16:41,532
So all the beads are different, but there's this string that goes through it, a continuity, a sort of self that continues, which is steady throughout the whole of these little apparitions.

149
00:16:41,511 --> 00:16:47,523
Whereas the Buddhist idea would be more a line of billiard balls that touch each other.

150
00:16:48,605 --> 00:16:49,866
So they're all quite distinct.

151
00:16:50,347 --> 00:16:53,011
All arising dependent on conditions.

152
00:16:53,714 --> 00:16:56,879
Not entirely the same, not entirely different.

153
00:16:57,740 --> 00:17:00,625
But always arising, always arising, one after the other.

154
00:17:00,745 --> 00:17:03,991
So it's a radical, it's a radical transience.

155
00:17:04,748 --> 00:17:32,426
so the Hindu idea might give you the impression of a lump of clay which you mould into a saucer screw it up again, mould it into a cup the same sort of substance that's moving around whereas the Buddhist idea is that there is nothing that actually moves it is more like well, the great example of course is the body the body itself

156
00:17:32,406 --> 00:17:39,175
So the body, according to our modern science, completely changes every atom.

157
00:17:39,455 --> 00:17:42,559
Every atom is supposed to be changed within seven years.

158
00:17:43,621 --> 00:17:49,689
So next time you look in a mirror, just remind yourself, this face wasn't here seven years ago.

159
00:17:51,431 --> 00:17:53,133
So get back to reality.

160
00:17:56,037 --> 00:17:57,398
So that's the difference.

161
00:17:57,419 --> 00:17:57,739
Yeah?

162
00:18:00,182 --> 00:18:05,632
So the next thing is, what are the proofs for rebirth, for reincarnation?

163
00:18:07,074 --> 00:18:19,275
There's a man called Stevenson who's spent his whole life going around, interviewing people, finding out about their recalls and rebirths and all that sort of stuff.

164
00:18:20,355 --> 00:18:26,747
And some of it is, in a sense, pretty convincing.

165
00:18:27,554 --> 00:18:31,260
Usually the most sharp ones come from children.

166
00:18:31,501 --> 00:18:37,874
Children suddenly around about the age of three to four or five suddenly remember things.

167
00:18:37,913 --> 00:18:46,490
There are stark examples where they've actually demanded to go and see their mother who lives in this next village.

168
00:18:47,163 --> 00:18:53,925
You know, when they take them off, they describe everybody, and they even tell how they died, and stuff like that.

169
00:18:53,986 --> 00:18:58,843
And it's sort of pretty heady stuff.

170
00:18:59,953 --> 00:19:17,337
The other one is of course adult past life experiences where a person remembers something happened in a past life and they can sometimes prove it, sometimes prove that it actually happened.

171
00:19:18,752 --> 00:19:21,659
And the other small thing is birthmarks caused by death.

172
00:19:22,140 --> 00:19:26,828
Often how you died is mirrored in the next body you get.

173
00:19:27,590 --> 00:19:36,228
So you get moles, and the next time you look at your moles, just say, these must have been stabbed here in my previous life.

174
00:19:36,248 --> 00:19:37,790
And birthmarks.

175
00:19:37,770 --> 00:19:41,576
So there are things like that which are supposed to relate.

176
00:19:41,856 --> 00:19:59,641
Again, proven by people with past life, who then said that they were shot, and there's a mole, there's a sort of birthmark, an ugly birthmark or something, where the bullet went in, things like that.

177
00:19:59,661 --> 00:20:02,664
Well, I'm just coming to that.

178
00:20:03,859 --> 00:20:20,836
The mark of a true past life experience, according to Stevenson and according to my understanding, is that the person remembers this past experience, re-experiences it as that person.

179
00:20:21,057 --> 00:20:22,598
So they're not this person.

180
00:20:22,919 --> 00:20:24,780
They're not actually this personality.

181
00:20:25,300 --> 00:20:29,125
It's as though for a moment you've become somebody else.

182
00:20:30,016 --> 00:20:43,839
And that can happen to us in a rebirth situation in this life where a childhood memory comes up as a trauma and you remember it as that child.

183
00:20:45,457 --> 00:20:46,398
So that's the difference.

184
00:20:46,439 --> 00:20:58,699
So if somebody says, you know, I suddenly remember being Napoleon at the Battle of Waterloo, then, you know, you can ask them, were you really Napoleon?

185
00:20:59,400 --> 00:21:00,401
Or just a memory, is it?

186
00:21:01,502 --> 00:21:09,455
And there are, of course, these other reasons as to why somebody might have past life recall.

187
00:21:09,992 --> 00:21:15,864
The first one, and this relates to Napoleon, is called Cryptomnesia.

188
00:21:16,144 --> 00:21:17,807
I don't know how they make these words up.

189
00:21:17,948 --> 00:21:18,650
Cryptomnesia.

190
00:21:21,134 --> 00:21:28,587
And the biggest example of that that most books use is concerning a woman called Virginia Teague.

191
00:21:29,390 --> 00:21:32,035
T-I-G-H-E, I don't know how you pronounce that.

192
00:21:32,892 --> 00:21:38,981
She certainly had these very vivid, clear memories of being Bridie Murphy in the south of Ireland in her past life.

193
00:21:39,202 --> 00:21:40,884
Described it absolutely perfectly.

194
00:21:41,866 --> 00:21:50,121
And from everybody's understanding, this is under hypnosis, so it wasn't something conscious, you might say.

195
00:21:50,821 --> 00:21:54,608
It seemed to be a real proof that past life exists.

196
00:21:54,749 --> 00:21:56,111
Because they went there and it was there.

197
00:21:56,131 --> 00:21:58,494
Everything was as she said it was.

198
00:21:58,474 --> 00:22:06,357
Then through an intrepid investigator they came across a certain Bridie Murphy.

199
00:22:07,739 --> 00:22:12,527
who actually lived opposite Virginia Tee and told her all these stories.

200
00:22:13,468 --> 00:22:22,402
And they'd obviously sunk into the subconscious, had taken on emotional meanings and came up as a whole story of vivid images.

201
00:22:23,364 --> 00:22:27,871
So that unfortunately was the end of this amazing proof that there was a past life.

202
00:22:28,752 --> 00:22:34,101
And now that's given the whole thing a bad name, you see, because now, well, it's just Kryptonnesia.

203
00:22:34,080 --> 00:22:36,904
I don't know what crypto means.

204
00:22:36,924 --> 00:22:37,384
What does it mean?

205
00:22:37,424 --> 00:22:38,266
I forgot to look it up.

206
00:22:39,468 --> 00:22:40,469
Hidden.

207
00:22:41,269 --> 00:22:46,056
So it's a hidden amnesia, a hidden forgetfulness, an unknown forgetfulness.

208
00:22:47,458 --> 00:22:47,778
Thank you.

209
00:22:49,420 --> 00:22:54,586
The other explanation, of course, from a materialist point of view, something like Dawkins or

210
00:22:54,989 --> 00:22:58,057
whatever, is genetic memory.

211
00:22:58,578 --> 00:23:10,010
So our genes not only carry just the physical nature of our bodies, but also they bring with it, like Dawkins calls them, memes.

212
00:23:09,990 --> 00:23:11,313
genes and memes.

213
00:23:12,294 --> 00:23:22,269
So the idea is that just as you get pieces of information in your genes which make up your body, you get pieces of information which are cultural.

214
00:23:22,409 --> 00:23:27,375
He doesn't refer to that in the genetic structure as far as I know.

215
00:23:27,415 --> 00:23:30,160
It's more in the sense that that's what we do to each other.

216
00:23:30,180 --> 00:23:38,731
We keep giving each other these little blocks of information which we then pass on and it builds up and builds up into a culture.

217
00:23:39,116 --> 00:23:45,364
So this idea that it's within our genes is something that people might argue, you see.

218
00:23:46,171 --> 00:23:48,733
The other one is just the power of retrocognition.

219
00:23:49,413 --> 00:23:54,559
The opposite of retrocognition is clairvoyance, where you can think where you have real...

220
00:23:55,141 --> 00:23:58,944
I mean, in clairvoyance, some people really do see what's going to happen.

221
00:23:59,505 --> 00:24:01,728
Sometimes they don't, but sometimes they really do.

222
00:24:02,367 --> 00:24:12,499
So this retrocognition may be real, maybe it did happen, etc., but it's more like a sort of mystical ability to see into the past.

223
00:24:13,778 --> 00:24:17,203
So there's your sort of arguments against it.

224
00:24:25,897 --> 00:24:30,346
It depends where you are on the scale of things, as to which one attracts you.

225
00:24:39,059 --> 00:24:40,241
The

226
00:24:43,224 --> 00:24:55,847
The bad thing about the whole rebirth, reincarnation theory, we can call it theory, is that of course for the self it becomes a comforting thought.

227
00:24:55,867 --> 00:24:57,089
So I won't die after all.

228
00:24:57,971 --> 00:24:58,712
I'll keep going.

229
00:24:58,813 --> 00:25:02,500
Even though I might have to go through this little gate and it's painful, I will arise.

230
00:25:05,820 --> 00:25:13,353
And to actually turn around and just face for a moment that in fact there is no re-arising of this person, which is true.

231
00:25:13,874 --> 00:25:15,777
This person will not re-arise.

232
00:25:17,519 --> 00:25:18,741
It's a bit of a, whoa!

233
00:25:21,065 --> 00:25:25,752
So to actually turn around and face the annihilation of this personality,

234
00:25:26,627 --> 00:25:30,373
is a bit of a challenge, a bit of a challenge.

235
00:25:31,355 --> 00:25:41,829
And it's sometimes easier to believe, well yes, the personality changes, but when I die, the changing will go on and I'll recognize me as I am, as I've always done.

236
00:25:45,694 --> 00:25:53,226
And of course the other awful thing about the whole rebirth understanding is that

237
00:25:56,647 --> 00:26:08,929
people delay the process of their liberation, thinking, well, now I'll just collect a bit of good karma, build up a good bank account, and I'll die in this lovely place, and off I go.

238
00:26:11,373 --> 00:26:13,336
So it's like you're delaying it, delaying it.

239
00:26:13,356 --> 00:26:18,345
And the whole idea of building up a bank account is based, of course, on a super ego.

240
00:26:18,846 --> 00:26:19,827
I mean, on a big ego.

241
00:26:20,008 --> 00:26:20,107
Yeah.

242
00:26:20,813 --> 00:26:27,598
That you're going to get more and more ability to liberate yourself the more good things you do.

243
00:26:28,099 --> 00:26:33,184
But the very fact that you're doing good things for that ego reason undermines the whole process.

244
00:26:34,786 --> 00:26:37,949
In other words, you're not facing the process of liberation.

245
00:26:39,430 --> 00:26:48,558
And, you know, for born Buddhists, for traditional Buddhists, I mean, most of them will delay it.

246
00:26:49,348 --> 00:26:58,628
It's not only the way, I would say, the vast majority of lay people, it's the way the vast majority of monks and nuns think.

247
00:26:58,648 --> 00:27:00,634
They're all building up good karma for the next life.

248
00:27:02,858 --> 00:27:09,432
So these are drawbacks of the belief in Reba.

249
00:27:15,538 --> 00:27:22,509
The other thing that comes across when you talk about rebirth is how do you square it up with evolution?

250
00:27:24,792 --> 00:27:25,594
Evolutionary theory.

251
00:27:25,994 --> 00:27:33,747
Now if you look at the Buddhist scripture they live in this ancient time of cyclic time.

252
00:27:34,468 --> 00:27:44,482
And this goes back to earlier times when, if you think about it, every year was virtually the same.

253
00:27:44,462 --> 00:27:45,684
And you did the same thing.

254
00:27:45,925 --> 00:27:47,469
And the society was static.

255
00:27:47,489 --> 00:27:54,080
For as long as you can remember and for as far as you can see, people will be doing the same thing over and over again.

256
00:27:55,364 --> 00:27:57,448
There was no idea of progress at all.

257
00:27:59,471 --> 00:28:03,940
Progress as such didn't really come into the Western mind.

258
00:28:03,920 --> 00:28:24,425
And it's a modern idea until fairly recently, although it was started off by, I believe, this cleric somewhere around the 12th century, if I remember rightly, who, having now been 12 centuries since the birth of Christ and he hadn't returned,

259
00:28:25,215 --> 00:28:30,742
began to say that the time before Christ's birth was the time of the Father.

260
00:28:31,644 --> 00:28:34,426
The time we're going through now is the time of Christ.

261
00:28:35,127 --> 00:28:39,854
And we're leading up to the time of the Spirit, when all will be resurrected.

262
00:28:40,454 --> 00:28:51,307
So this idea of actually going somewhere, of an aim, of an end to life, suddenly appears before us as an evolutionary process.

263
00:28:51,288 --> 00:28:55,656
This of course was reinforced by Darwin and all that we know these days.

264
00:28:57,359 --> 00:29:04,755
Although they say you can pick holes in the theory, I don't know enough about it to give you that.

265
00:29:05,496 --> 00:29:10,326
The fact is it's pretty convincing stuff that there's a process of evolution going on.

266
00:29:12,752 --> 00:29:18,167
Whereas if you read the scriptures, what you get is the name of the past 28 Buddhas.

267
00:29:19,270 --> 00:29:28,737
And every Buddha has a Pali name, they have two main disciples, they go through this and it's this repetition, repetition.

268
00:29:29,205 --> 00:29:48,227
If you lived in those times and all you thought, considering you were, say, a farmer, working with your ox on a field day after day, you know, no TV, no holidays, except in winter when it's dry season.

269
00:29:48,207 --> 00:29:58,281
You go through this, and then you have to go through these horrible old days because there's no medicine, and there may be some palliatives for pain, and people have died, their teeth are falling out.

270
00:29:59,263 --> 00:29:59,483
You see?

271
00:29:59,964 --> 00:30:02,208
And leprosy, oh God.

272
00:30:02,588 --> 00:30:03,810
And the whole thing is there.

273
00:30:03,871 --> 00:30:07,296
When you're going to die, say, I don't want to come back here.

274
00:30:07,276 --> 00:30:12,669
So this idea of being reborn was really quite the big thing in the Buddha's time.

275
00:30:13,069 --> 00:30:15,255
Everybody wanted the end of rebirth.

276
00:30:15,275 --> 00:30:23,934
They wanted, you know, not to be brought back as a human being, to be born into a god, not to fall down from the gods to be a human being.

277
00:30:23,914 --> 00:30:25,877
And it was pretty obsessive.

278
00:30:26,038 --> 00:30:32,047
And it actually ends up in the three great insights of the Buddha's enlightenment.

279
00:30:32,087 --> 00:30:32,949
That's where it's put.

280
00:30:33,390 --> 00:30:35,792
It's called the Te Vidya, the three knowledges.

281
00:30:35,833 --> 00:30:45,086
The first knowledge is that he sees that the process of his rebirth has been very much according to his moral life.

282
00:30:46,068 --> 00:30:51,356
So whereas before the Buddha, the idea was that it was more...

283
00:30:51,336 --> 00:30:53,800
a chaotic reason, you just got reborn.

284
00:30:53,820 --> 00:30:58,988
The only way you could get out of this rebirth was through ritual, through appeasing the gods.

285
00:30:59,769 --> 00:31:04,776
There wasn't a close relationship with rebirth and your moral life, your ethical life.

286
00:31:05,396 --> 00:31:09,462
So this was an insight into the fact that it's our morality

287
00:31:10,169 --> 00:31:12,271
Morality here means what is skillful.

288
00:31:12,833 --> 00:31:15,435
It's not just to do with killing and whatnot.

289
00:31:15,537 --> 00:31:22,846
It's to do with all that stuff around you, what we might call these days little neurotic patterns and stuff like that.

290
00:31:23,166 --> 00:31:26,090
It's the purification of the heart.

291
00:31:26,111 --> 00:31:30,037
And then through his vision, he saw that this was true of all beings.

292
00:31:30,057 --> 00:31:32,640
So what was a personal law became a cosmic law.

293
00:31:33,381 --> 00:31:38,808
And the third understanding was that he'd actually completely purified his heart.

294
00:31:39,211 --> 00:31:43,976
Now, to be an arahat, to be a fully enlightened being, it's the third one you have to do.

295
00:31:44,076 --> 00:31:45,897
You don't have to have these other insights.

296
00:31:46,939 --> 00:31:54,468
So there's a small suggestion that these sort of crept in, you might say, as part of the whole teaching around karma.

297
00:31:56,589 --> 00:32:05,859
Part of the whole teaching around how we create karma, the process of karma, how it's guided by what is skillful and unskillful, etc., etc.,

298
00:32:10,665 --> 00:32:15,071
In terms of these days, does rebirth make sense?

299
00:32:16,433 --> 00:32:29,751
Well, I suppose if you think of it as an evolutionary process, that you're actually moving towards a liberated consciousness, a liberated chitta, you might say, then it is some sort of an evolutionary process.

300
00:32:29,832 --> 00:32:31,113
It still seems to work.

301
00:32:34,498 --> 00:32:36,740
It's the evolution of consciousness, you might say.

302
00:32:43,015 --> 00:32:44,233
Um...

303
00:32:49,478 --> 00:32:54,982
The other thing that comes across is the question about seeming inequality.

304
00:32:55,563 --> 00:33:00,768
I mean, people seem to die who've been absolute villains and they seem to die in bed and fairly happy.

305
00:33:01,628 --> 00:33:07,034
And others who've been wonderful and good end up on the jibbit and get themselves hanged.

306
00:33:08,674 --> 00:33:10,057
I mean, how does that work?

307
00:33:10,136 --> 00:33:14,921
Well, there are all sorts of, as we say, ways of trying to explain that.

308
00:33:15,320 --> 00:33:19,484
But one thing you have to understand about karma is that

309
00:33:19,464 --> 00:33:27,291
Our moral life is only to do with our internal, our interior life.

310
00:33:28,512 --> 00:33:29,753
Of course it affects others.

311
00:33:30,114 --> 00:33:32,576
I mean, if I'm into stealing, that's going to affect people.

312
00:33:33,057 --> 00:33:35,098
If I'm into good works, it's going to affect people.

313
00:33:35,618 --> 00:33:47,970
But morality, my ethical life, has a direct effect upon my inner life and eventually should clear it up, should move it towards a purification.

314
00:33:48,675 --> 00:33:55,501
But things that happen to me on the outside, of course, are coming from other sources.

315
00:33:55,642 --> 00:33:59,965
I mean, it might be that I steal something and I get caught and put in jail.

316
00:33:59,986 --> 00:34:03,970
So that's a fairly straightforward sequence of events that I can understand.

317
00:34:03,990 --> 00:34:11,496
It may be that I do some little good for somebody and they turn out to be a billionaire and they give me a million pounds.

318
00:34:11,516 --> 00:34:18,682
So I can see how wonderful that is if you find anybody like that, by the way.

319
00:34:18,663 --> 00:34:25,132
But unfortunately, suddenly you win the lottery.

320
00:34:26,213 --> 00:34:31,101
Suddenly you find yourself caught up in a terrorist ordeal.

321
00:34:31,201 --> 00:34:37,289
All these people at the moment getting kidnapped in Iraq.

322
00:34:39,213 --> 00:34:45,581
So obviously we live in a fairly chaotic universe in the sense that we don't know what's going to happen to us.

323
00:34:45,730 --> 00:34:47,918
Because there are various forces.

324
00:34:47,998 --> 00:34:49,585
There is the force of nature.

325
00:34:49,826 --> 00:34:56,010
There's the force of other people's decision-making and actions towards us.

326
00:34:57,070 --> 00:35:03,797
So you have to take all that into account when you think about, well, why did that happen to that person?

327
00:35:03,918 --> 00:35:05,358
Why did they die in this way?

328
00:35:05,378 --> 00:35:06,539
Why didn't they die this way?

329
00:35:07,882 --> 00:35:11,045
Because we're not in control of the situation we're in.

330
00:35:12,025 --> 00:35:19,855
But one little example that I like to give around that is that in one of the great earthquakes, I think it was in Mexico,

331
00:35:19,835 --> 00:35:26,802
they found this mother and her child after something like 10 days trapped just between two blocks.

332
00:35:28,043 --> 00:35:35,771
And the mother had, over the period of 10 days, constantly cut her fingers in order to feed the child her blood.

333
00:35:40,295 --> 00:35:45,621
So, you know, presumably they were fairly comfortable down there for the time being.

334
00:35:46,101 --> 00:35:48,724
But it's like, you know, that's quite a bit.

335
00:35:48,764 --> 00:35:49,824
She didn't freak out.

336
00:36:02,275 --> 00:36:07,952
And finally, I suppose, a big question.

337
00:36:09,175 --> 00:36:11,543
Is the concept of rebirth necessary?

338
00:36:12,873 --> 00:36:15,797
to become enlightened or to get the best out of the Buddha Dhamma.

339
00:36:16,719 --> 00:36:29,963
And I think you'll find amongst Western people, Western scholars and Western Buddhists, and there's one, if you look up the Journal of Buddhist Ethics on the web, you'll get some very good essays about it.

340
00:36:29,983 --> 00:36:34,610
The general opinion is, of course, that you don't need to believe it at all.

341
00:36:35,030 --> 00:36:38,398
The Dharma itself either works now or it doesn't work at all.

342
00:36:38,858 --> 00:36:45,996
One sees the benefit now, here and now, sanditiko, here and now, or what's the point of it?

343
00:36:47,239 --> 00:36:47,418
Is it?

344
00:36:47,855 --> 00:36:58,224
and worries about whether there is a future life or not, really don't pertain to the direct practice.

345
00:36:58,244 --> 00:37:13,659
So the wheel of dependent origination, which is this whole process of mentation, which brings about the purification, or which upon seeing of it, the seeing of it, seeing how we cause ourselves suffering, is the process of liberation.

346
00:37:13,639 --> 00:37:38,652
is happening right here and now so the escape is here and now from that so it's not actually necessary for the Dharma to work and just to leave you with one little understanding that the Buddha gives in this Kalama Sutta which is a sort of discourse where he really talks about freedom of thought and things like that he says well

347
00:37:39,306 --> 00:37:53,547
If you live with the idea that there will be a rebirth and that your good actions here and now will produce a better life, if there is rebirth, all well and good.

348
00:37:54,768 --> 00:37:57,152
If there isn't rebirth, all well and good.

349
00:37:58,715 --> 00:38:02,900
In other words, the reason for our practice has nothing to do with whether there's rebirth or not.

350
00:38:06,947 --> 00:38:17,099
So, in terms of your practice now, here, at Gaia House, this whole talk has been a waste of time.

351
00:38:19,543 --> 00:38:23,949
Because it's irrelevant.

352
00:38:23,969 --> 00:38:32,759
But it's a pleasant three-quarters of an hour.

353
00:38:32,778 --> 00:38:32,958
Good.

354
00:38:33,340 --> 00:38:35,081
I think that's about it.

